AGI - A huge Piazza del Ferrarese a&nbsp;Bari: citizens, political representatives, mayors, young students, all drawn around their city and mayor Antonio Decaro, with the slogan "Let the hands da&nbsp;Bari&nbsp;#iostoconDecaro", the event called by Cgil and Pd as a sign of solidarity to the first citizen and the administration after the news of the arrival of the measure of inspective access provided by the minister of the Interior to the Municipality of.Bari. From the stage the students are reconstructing the history of the "Internal Code" investigation, which has unleashed the Parisi-Palermiti clans, with 137 arrests, and highlighted ties with some political representatives. The stages of the affair led the Minister of the Interior, Matteo Piantedosi, to appoint an Antimafia Access Commission to the Commune. Fischi were addressed to Maurizio Gasparri and the parliamentarians of the district, who asked the Viminale in depth.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
On the case Bari wanted to say his vice-premier and foreign minister, Antonio&nbsp;Tajani: "I believe that minister Piantedosi did well to form a team that will go to control what happened. I am a guarantee, I do not point the index against anyone, but we must always ascertain the truth. I don't think it's about the mayor's person, but something strange is there, especially in the transport company, there you have to turn on the spotlight, I'm guaranteed but 130 arrests in a city are not a little bit. It's right to make sure that no one is guilty. Access to acts is an act of transparency, not of accusation", concluded&nbsp;Tajani.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
Decaro, "we are not blackmailed or mafia or politics">
&nbsp;
"I didn't come to argue. Many people have told me to answer that MP, I do not answer because the best answer is here in front of me, in this square, it is you. The best answer to those who want to use this city to campaign, to those who say that Bari is under the blackmail of the mafia: is no longer under the blackmail or the mafia or politics." This was said by the mayor of Bari, Antonio Decaro, from the stage of the event "Giù le mani da Bari", who recorded almost 20 thousand presences according to the organizers (6000, according to Digos). "This city - it has added - in these 20 years, with sacrifices, with sweat, with daily work has grown up, has recovered its dignity. Today Bari is proud of what has become in these years and we are no longer ashamed, we are bare and we are proud to be. Today when we look at you today we all feel bare also the mayors, the citizens, who have come from the rest of our region. But also from the rest of our country. I'll defend this city until the last day I'm mayor. I will defend the honor of the city of Bari, along with you. I will try as mayor to be up to this wonderful answer you gave us. I will try to be up to your pride, your dignity, your great love." &nbsp;
&nbsp;<br> And again: "What they are trying to make us is an unbounded shame - Decaro continued -. Because you don't walk through a city just for an electoral calculation, maybe for a win at a coffee table, you don't trample a city, the future of the Baresis, just because you're afraid to lose the election campaign, which has been lost for 20 years, because they've never had a project, an idea for this city. We are bare, we are in love with this city that we will defend, dear ladies and gentlemen. You may also dissolve the city council, but you will not be able to dissolve the bond that keeps us all together in this square."
<br> Emiliano, "the government has the obsession to win the elections here">
&nbsp;
"When people like those happen to the government, things like these happen. And the responsibility of our national leaders must much more intense, because that is the same government that is varating the differentiated autonomy, that wants to strike the South in its freedom, that it wants to commissariare in that logic, has come to the point of imagining, using anti-mafia prevention measures, to win the elections in Bari, because winning the elections in Bari is, of course, for them, an obsession". This was said by the president of the Puglia Region, Michele Emiliano, on stage of the event "Giù le mani da Bari", talking about the arrival of the Antimafia Access Commission to the Municipality.
Emiliano recalled, citing a video shot by premier Giorgia Meloni in via Sparano during the electoral campaign for the past policies, "talk to me directly - said the governor - almost in an intimidating manner, and he said to me 'this is your Bari, is that what you have built? We'll show you. It was a promise that he did that day and he's keeping it wrong. Using means that, instead, have another purpose, have another meaning. It is absolutely not true what they say, that it was a due act. There is no obligation, as for criminal action, to act with preventive measures. There was no urgency, because these investigations could be done even after the elections. Also because the administration is melting itself by natural line, by expiry of the mandate. They need this inspection to build on an election campaign - accused Emiliano -. That's the shame! They don't know what to say. They don't have shoes, they don't have bicycles, they don't know what you think, they don't know how you live, they don't know what your problems are, and they think they convince you to vote against this community with the excuse of prevention measures." &nbsp;
<br> Bonaccini, "the dissolution of the administration is incomprehensible" >
&nbsp;
"Bari with Antonio Decaro. We with Antonio Decaro. Maximum respect for the work of the prosecutor: To combat and eradicate organized crime is an absolute priority of all institutions. Report that the Prosecutor of Bari has emphasized how the municipal administration Decaro has spent in these years for the legality and contrast of the mafias. That now the government activates a procedure that can lead to the dissolution of the municipal administration, for more than three months from the vote, is frankly incomprehensible. That this choice then descends from a summit at the Viminale between the Minister and some Apulian parliamentarians is disturbing." Thus, in a post on Facebook, the president of the Pd and the Emilia-Romagna Region Stefano Bonaccini. "I reaffirm my total closeness to Antonio Decaro and my trust in the work of the magistrates. I find vice versa incomprehensible the choice of the government. If it is dictated by things that we do not know have the duty to tell us and to tell the citizens of Bari, otherwise the suspicion of a political act assumed against an unwelcome administration," concluded Bonaccini.
&nbsp;

