AGI - The Board of Directors of the AGI, in application of the mandate conferred unanimously by the Assembly of Editors of 18 March last, proclaims two days of strike from midnight of 20 March until 23:59 of 22 March, found the absence of an early official response from the Company on the future owner of the agency. Despite the formal requests for clarification on the sales hypotheses, advanced first through the communiqué of the Assembly of Editors and then through the formal request of an urgent meeting submitted by the Board, the Company so far has not provided any response in the opinion of having to confront the internal union body.
The insistent indiscretions and news about the possible sale of the agency arrive a few weeks after the signing, on 2 February last, of the agreement between Cdr, Company and Fnsi on the procedure of openness, destined to determine within the year a sensitive reduction of the staff. An agreement - approved with great sense of responsibility by the Assembly of editors - to which it had arrived even after the verbal reassurances provided by the corporate leadership on the absence of negotiations in existence for a sale, underlined by the presence of a strategic plan 2024-2027 aimed at "implementing the transformation strategy in a news company".
For more than 70 years AGI has been a reference point for Italian information and has always provided quality and pluralist news. Over the years, Eni has been a publisher who has been able to safeguard the occupational levels and always guarantee the independence and autonomy of journalists, all elements that would be strongly at risk in the planned scenario of sale to the Angelucci publishing group. In this possible sale we believe both the guarantee of pluralism of information of the Country: a press agency, a primary source of information, is in fact pluralistic and impartial &nbsp;

